<TABLE CELLPADDING=3 CELLSPACING=0 BORDER=0>
<TR><TD BGCOLOR="9f9fFF"><STRONG>Reference Material</STRONG></TD></TR>
<TR><TD>
This page contains useful web links, and other documentation and reference material 
related to CS 337/437. Some of this material is provided by other web sites and may 
change, so please tell us if you notice a problem with these links or they do not 
seem useful to you.
</TD></tr>

<TR><TD BGCOLOR="cfcfFF"><dd>General Distributed Systems</TD></TR>
<tr><td><table CELLPADDING=3 CELLSPACING=5 BORDER=0>
<tr><td BGCOLOR="ffcfcf">
Building Secure and Reliable Network Applications<br>
Kenneth P. Birman 1996<br>
<a href="http://www.manning.com/Birman/index.html">http://www.manning.com/Birman/index.html</a>
</td><td BGCOLOR="cfffcf">
This is a recommended book for many of the topics covered in lecture. It is currently
out of print so it is difficult to purchase a copy. If you are interested, I believe
the publisher still has copies available for purchase at the books website.
</td>

</tr><tr><td BGCOLOR="ffcfcf">
Distributed Systems: Concepts and Design<br>
George Coulouris, Jean Dollimore and Tim Kindberg 2001<br>
<a href="http://www.cdk3.net/">http://www.cdk3.net/</a>
</td><td BGCOLOR="cfffcf">
This is a good, updated, textbook covering a lot of distributed systems. It does not have
as much focus on reliable systems as we do in this course.
</td>

</tr>
</table>

<TR><TD BGCOLOR="cfcfFF"><dd>General Networking</TD></TR>
<tr><td><table CELLPADDING=3 CELLSPACING=5 BORDER=0>
<tr><td BGCOLOR="ffcfcf">
An Engineering Approach to Computer Networking<br>
S. Keshav 1997<br>
</td><td BGCOLOR="cfffcf">
This book gives a good comparison between several differnt networking families 
(ATM, Telephone, Internet). For internet related protocols it is more engineering focused
with some rigorous analysis of why things are done the way they are.
</td>

</tr><tr><td BGCOLOR="ffcfcf">
Internetworking with TCP/IP Volume 1<br>
Douglas E. Comer 1995<br>
</td><td BGCOLOR="cfffcf">
Complete coverage of everything related to Internet protocols. Excellent if you want to examine
the protocols in depth.
</td>

</tr><tr><td BGCOLOR="ffcfcf">
Data and Computer Communications, 5th edition<br>
William Stallings 1997<br>
</td><td BGCOLOR="cfffcf">
Rigorous coverage of all forms of networking. Much more in depth then we cover in this
class, but if you want more details this is a good place.
</td>

</tr>
</table>

<TR><TD BGCOLOR="cfcfFF"><dd>Network Programming</TD></TR>
<tr><td><table CELLPADDING=3 CELLSPACING=5 BORDER=0>
<tr><td BGCOLOR="ffcfcf">
Unix Network Programming: Volume 1 Sockets and XTI<br>
Richard Stevens 1998 2nd Edition<br>
<a href="http://www.kohala.com/start/unpv12e.html">http://www.kohala.com/start/unpv12e.html</a>
</td><td BGCOLOR="cfffcf">
This is the Best sockets programming book out there. For both learning and reference
it is excellent. The website above is the site for the book and has information like
the table of contents, errata, a sample chapter, source code, etc.
</td>

<TR><TD BGCOLOR="ffcfcf">
<a href="http://homepages.stayfree.co.uk/zed/net/">http://homepages.stayfree.co.uk/zed/net/</a>
</td><td BGCOLOR="cfffcf">
Network programming tutorials.
</td>

<tr><td BGCOLOR="ffcfcf">
<a href="http://www.stardust.com/wsresource/wsresrce.html">http://www.stardust.com/winsock/index.html</a>
</td><td BGCOLOR="cfffcf">
A WinSock programming source. Winsock is very similar to standard BSD sockets and
might be more familiar to windows programmers. HOWEVER, since all C programs must
run on the solaris machines you DO NOT want to actually program using this.
</td>
<tr><td BGCOLOR="ffcfcf">
<a href="http://www.ecst.csuchico.edu/~beej/guide/net/">http://www.ecst.csuchico.edu/~beej/guide/net/</a>
</td><td BGCOLOR="cfffcf">
A guide to network programming. This is very friendly to beginners.
</td>

</tr>
<tr><td BGCOLOR="ffcfcf">
<a href="http://www.faqs.org/faqs/unix-faq/socket/index.html">http://www.faqs.org/faqs/unix-faq/socket/index.html</a>
</td><td BGCOLOR="cfffcf">
This is a FAQ about Unix sockets (the week1 tutorial).
</td>

</tr>
<tr><td BGCOLOR="ffcfcf">

</td><td BGCOLOR="cfffcf">

</td>

</tr>
</table>
<tr><td BGCOLOR="cfcfff"><dd>C programming and Unix library functions</td></tr>
<tr><td><table CELLPADDING=3 CELLSPACING=5 BORDER=0>
<tr><td BGCOLOR="ffcfcf">
<a href="http://www.cs.utah.edu/dept/old/texinfo/glibc-manual-0.02/library_toc.html">http://www.cs.utah.edu/dept/old/texinfo/glibc-manual-0.02/library_toc.html</a>
</td><td BGCOLOR="cfffcf">
The C library documentation in HTML format.
</td>

<tr></table>
</TR></TABLE>
